{"key":"post-12286537","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12286537</id>\n<content>Several years ago I offered a free microscope to the first person who could grow a ten gram or larger(wet) mushroom by hydroponics.&amp;nbsp; There's been many people wasting time trying but no success.&amp;nbsp; Mushrooms digest and consume food much closer to the way humans do than plants.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It's good that the mycelium produces enzymes that becomes more acidic over time.&amp;nbsp; Mushroom mycelium colonizes fastest at around a pH of 5 to 6, and fruits best at 4.5 to 5.5.&amp;nbsp; In my farm, I dunk substrates in water with citric acid added to lower pH.&amp;nbsp; You don't need to lower pH when making up bulk substrates because most are already close to what we need.&amp;nbsp; Use gypsum to prevent wild swings in pH and to supply minerals.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12287316</next>\n<prev>12285946</prev>\n<first>12275169</first>\n<last>12633184</last>\n<when>1269785219</when>\n<utime>03/28/10 05:06 PM</utime>\n</post>"}